Great idea. To illustrate the difference, let’s look at a common scenario: sending a JSON POST request with Basic Authentication.

Notice how the syntax changes from "manual labor" in cURL to a more "human-friendly" style in HTTPie and Curlie.

Comparison: POST Request with Auth
Suppose we want to send a JSON payload {"name": "Alice"} to an API that requires a username and password.

1. cURL
You have to manually set the content type, specify the POST method, and stringify your JSON.

Bash
curl -u admin:password \
     -X POST \
     -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
     -d '{"name": "Alice"}' \
     https://api.example.com/users
2. HTTPie
HTTPie assumes you want JSON and handles the headers for you. The key-value pairs at the end are automatically converted to a JSON object.

Bash
http -a admin:password POST https://api.example.com/users name=Alice
3. Curlie
Curlie allows you to use the exact same syntax as HTTPie, but it actually passes the command through to curl.

Bash
curlie -u admin:password POST https://api.example.com/users name=Alice
Pro Tip: Because Curlie is just a wrapper, you can also mix and match. If you need a specific cURL flag like --insecure (or -k) that HTTPie doesn't handle the same way, you can just add it: curlie -k POST ...

Which should you choose for your workflow?
Use Case	Recommended Tool
Production scripts / CI/CD	curl (Guaranteed to be there and never breaks).
Exploratory API Testing	httpie (Best UI/UX and highest readability).
Developer "Daily Driver"	curlie (HTTPie's ease with cURL's speed/features).
