You said
what can httpie do that curlie cannot?

Gemini said
While curlie is a fantastic hybrid, httpie is a more mature and feature-rich ecosystem. If curlie is a "power wrapper," httpie is a full-fledged "suite."

Here are the specific things HTTPie can do that Curlie cannot (or doesn't do as well):

1. Persistent Sessions
This is arguably HTTPie's "killer feature." HTTPie can save session information (like cookies and custom headers) and automatically reuse them in subsequent requests.

HTTPie: http --session=my-login-session example.org/login username=admin

The Benefit: On your next request, you don't have to re-authenticate or manually pass cookie headers; HTTPie just "remembers" you're logged in. Curlie (via curl) requires you to manually manage "cookie jar" files.

2. Advanced JSON Construction
While both support simple key=value JSON, HTTPie has a much more powerful syntax for nested or typed JSON data directly from the CLI without writing raw JSON strings.

Nested Data: http POST api.example.com/data 'user[name]=Alice' 'user[age]:=30'

Non-string types: Using := tells HTTPie to parse the value as JSON (numbers, booleans, or arrays) rather than a string.

3. The Desktop & Web App Ecosystem
HTTPie is no longer just a CLI tool. They have a full ecosystem that includes:

Desktop App: A graphical interface (similar to Postman) that syncs with your CLI work.

Web Version: You can use httpie.io/run in a browser to test APIs without installing anything.

Cloud Sync: You can save requests into "Spaces" and "Collections" that sync across the CLI and Desktop app. Curlie is strictly a CLI wrapper.

4. Plugin System
Since HTTPie is written in Python, it has a robust plugin architecture. You can install community-developed plugins for:

Specialized Auth: Like httpie-aws-auth for signing AWS requests.

New Protocols: Supporting things like EdgeGrid or other niche standards.

Custom Formatters: If you want your output to look a very specific way.

5. Smarter "Human" Defaults
HTTPie is designed to be opinionated for humans. For example:

URL Shortcuts: In HTTPie, you can often omit http:// or even the hostname if you use a configuration file for a specific "base URL."

Binary Handling: HTTPie is much safer when accidentally requesting binary data (like a .zip file); it won't dump the "garbage" text into your terminal by default, whereas curl (and thus curlie) might require you to be more careful.

Summary Table
Feature	HTTPie	Curlie
Named Sessions	Yes (Automated)	No (Manual via curl flags)
Nested JSON Syntax	Yes (Complex nested objects)	Limited (Simple key/value)
GUI / Desktop App	Yes	No
Plugin Architecture	Yes (Python-based)	No
Speed	Slower (Python)	Faster (Go + cURL)
